WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.030
[Music]

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:11.550
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. Today in&nbsp;
this series on the foundations of algebra,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:11.550 --> 00:00:17.850
we're going to answer the very important&nbsp;
question of what exactly is a polynomial.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:17.850 --> 00:00:25.590
A polynomial is a fundamental building block of&nbsp;
algebra, and in most treatments of the subject,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:25.590 --> 00:00:30.960
it's introduced only in a vague&nbsp;
and imprecise way. But fundamental&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:30.960 --> 00:00:34.530
building blocks of mathematics&nbsp;
have to be defined very precisely.

00:00:34.530 --> 00:00:40.080
So I remind you that the usual idea is that&nbsp;
a polynomial is some kind of expression&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:40.080 --> 00:00:46.800
involving an unknown variable or general&nbsp;
variable, x, or perhaps y, or perhaps a,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:46.800 --> 00:00:53.910
or perhaps b. And this polynomial is allowed&nbsp;
to have various manifestations or different&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:53.910 --> 00:00:58.770
expressions. The idea is that it should be&nbsp;
built up just from the three operations:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:58.770 --> 00:01:05.370
addition, subtraction, and multiplication. So&nbsp;
these are all considered polynomials in x in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:05.370 --> 00:01:10.680
the usual formulation of things. Another&nbsp;
approach is to think of a polynomial as a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:10.680 --> 00:01:17.370
function—something that inputs an x and outputs&nbsp;
another number given by an expression like this.

00:01:17.370 --> 00:01:24.150
Alright, so our approach is going to be a&nbsp;
little bit different. Roughly, our idea is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:24.150 --> 00:01:34.620
that a polynomial is a polynomial form; in fact,&nbsp;
it's a particular form that involves linear&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:34.620 --> 00:01:40.320
combinations of something we're going to call&nbsp;
alpha. I'll tell you what alpha is in a second,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:40.320 --> 00:01:46.830
but here are some examples of the kind of thing&nbsp;
that we're interested in establishing. So this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:46.830 --> 00:01:54.750
would be something like a polynomial P = 3 + 5α&nbsp;
+ 27α². It’s what you would usually think of as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:54.750 --> 00:02:01.920
a polynomial in alpha, but we'll prefer to write&nbsp;
this rather in this more laborious fashion. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:01.920 --> 00:02:09.450
instead of 3, we'll write 3α⁰; instead of α,&nbsp;
we'll write α¹, so that the powers of alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:09.450 --> 00:02:15.930
are increasing from 0 onwards. That's what&nbsp;
a polynomial for us is going to look like.

00:02:15.930 --> 00:02:22.020
And now I have to tell you how do we connect&nbsp;
this to poly numbers and what is this object&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:22.020 --> 00:02:28.800
alpha. We've made the observation before that&nbsp;
a poly number with just one entry at the top,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:35.760
the degree zero spot, acts essentially like&nbsp;
a number. The arithmetic for those poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:42.240
numbers is just the same as the arithmetic for&nbsp;
ordinary numbers. So the first poly number that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:42.240 --> 00:02:47.850
goes beyond that arithmetic is this one right&nbsp;
here, the poly number (0, 1), and that's what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:47.850 --> 00:02:54.780
we are calling alpha. So alpha for us is just&nbsp;
a particular poly number—that one right there.

00:02:54.780 --> 00:03:00.300
Alright, then it's easy to check&nbsp;
that α² is the poly number (0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:00.300 --> 00:03:08.070
0, 1), and α³ will be (0, 0, 0, 1),&nbsp;
and in general, any power of alpha,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:09.150 --> 00:03:17.070
say α^k, will be a string of k zeros and then&nbsp;
a 1. That means we can rewrite a general poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:17.070 --> 00:03:24.000
number as a linear combination of these&nbsp;
powers of alpha. For example, (2, 7, 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:42.000
3) can be written as 2α⁰ + 7α¹ + 3α³ (we've left&nbsp;
out the α² term because its coefficient is zero).

00:03:44.700 --> 00:03:51.660
This poly number (0, 0, 0, 13, 0, 52)&nbsp;
can be written in a rather short way&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:51.660 --> 00:04:04.410
by just ignoring the zeros and writing&nbsp;
13α³ + 52α⁵. And so we say this is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:04.410 --> 00:04:10.080
standard form for a poly number, or if we want&nbsp;
to be more specific, the standard alpha form,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:10.080 --> 00:04:17.040
where we write out the poly number in powers&nbsp;
of alpha and we use this convention for α⁰,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:17.040 --> 00:04:25.410
α¹, α², α³, and so on. We agree to leave out&nbsp;
the coefficients with zero, as in this case&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:25.410 --> 00:04:33.000
here, where we don't write 0α⁰ + 0α¹ and so on,&nbsp;
except in one special case—the zero polynomial.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:42.570
We'll write that as 0α⁰. We have to write&nbsp;
something, and so that's what we'll write.

00:04:42.570 --> 00:04:50.520
So you can see one of the advantages of&nbsp;
this standard alpha form for a poly number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.520 --> 00:04:55.440
namely that when the poly number&nbsp;
has lots of zeros in it, we save&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:55.440 --> 00:05:01.140
ourselves the trouble of having to write&nbsp;
all those zeros. We're just concentrating&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:01.140 --> 00:05:06.180
on the terms which have strictly&nbsp;
positive entries, nonzero entries.

00:05:06.180 --> 00:05:17.010
So here then is our main definition: a positive&nbsp;
polynomial is a positive poly number written in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:17.010 --> 00:05:29.220
standard alpha form. So a polynomial is just a&nbsp;
poly number written in a particular way. This is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:29.220 --> 00:05:35.010
then not a new mathematical object; we're still&nbsp;
just talking about positive poly numbers, but&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:35.010 --> 00:05:41.550
we're writing them in a new way. We've seen this&nbsp;
before, actually. When we started off this series,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:41.550 --> 00:05:49.080
we defined natural numbers as a string of ones—I&nbsp;
hope you remember that was the definition of what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:49.080 --> 00:05:56.580
a natural number was—but then at some point,&nbsp;
we changed in practice to writing a natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:56.580 --> 00:06:02.460
number not as a string of ones but in terms of&nbsp;
the Hindu-Arabic system. So now, when we write&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:02.460 --> 00:06:07.740
a natural number like 345, we're not writing a&nbsp;
whole bunch of ones; we're just writing 3, 4,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:07.740 --> 00:06:14.460
or 5. But really, it's the same mathematical&nbsp;
object, just written in a new way. It's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:14.460 --> 00:06:19.920
convenient in mathematics to have alternate ways&nbsp;
of writing sometimes the same mathematical object.

00:06:19.920 --> 00:06:27.000
So please stop the video now and have a look&nbsp;
at these eight examples and try to figure out&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:31.980
which of these are positive polynomials.&nbsp;
Alright, I'll give you a moment to think.

00:06:34.410 --> 00:06:34.440
[Pause]

00:06:34.440 --> 00:06:41.610
Okay, so the answer is: only one of them. The&nbsp;
first one is a positive polynomial, and the rest&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:41.610 --> 00:06:48.240
are not. Let's see why not. This one here has&nbsp;
a negative sign. We so far have not introduced&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:48.240 --> 00:06:55.890
negative signs—all the coefficients have to be&nbsp;
positive natural numbers. Later on, of course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:55.890 --> 00:06:59.400
we're going to include that as a possibility&nbsp;
too, but right now, we're just talking about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:59.400 --> 00:07:06.780
positive polynomials. What about this one? Well,&nbsp;
we're being a little bit fussy here. This 4 does&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:06.780 --> 00:07:12.960
not have an α⁰ in front of it. We insist that&nbsp;
all the terms have coefficients times powers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:12.960 --> 00:07:17.820
of alpha. The trouble with allowing something&nbsp;
like this is that it's easy to get confused&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:17.820 --> 00:07:25.920
between this number 4 being an actual number or&nbsp;
being a poly number. We want numbers and poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:25.920 --> 00:07:31.320
numbers to be different objects technically,&nbsp;
so that's why we're not going to allow this.

00:07:31.320 --> 00:07:38.310
How about this? This seems to be alright, but it's&nbsp;
not because it's not written out in the standard&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:38.310 --> 00:07:44.520
form. The standard form requires that you start&nbsp;
with the degree 0 term, then the degree 1 term,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:44.520 --> 00:07:49.860
then the degree 2 term, and so on. Well, you might&nbsp;
say, "Well, you could expand this," and you could,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:49.860 --> 00:07:56.520
but that's not something that we want to do. If&nbsp;
you give me an example of a positive poly number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:56.520 --> 00:08:01.980
it better be in the required form, unlike a&nbsp;
computer; otherwise, I'm not going to accept&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:01.980 --> 00:08:09.060
it. So in other words, I'm not willing to do&nbsp;
the work involved in expanding this out and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:09.060 --> 00:08:15.420
putting it in standard form. The person coming&nbsp;
with the object has to do that work themselves.

00:08:15.420 --> 00:08:22.380
What's wrong with 0? Well, we agree&nbsp;
that 0 is going to be written 0 times&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:22.380 --> 00:08:28.170
α⁰ because it's level 0, so it should have&nbsp;
an α⁰ in front of it. How about this one:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:28.170 --> 00:08:34.350
α⁷ + 2α⁴? It's not in the standard form.&nbsp;
The powers of alpha have to be increasing.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:34.350 --> 00:08:42.840
αⁿ and α^m—these are variable things. They're&nbsp;
not powers of alpha in the sense that we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:42.840 --> 00:08:47.490
talking about—there have to be natural&nbsp;
numbers up here. How about 2α⁴ + α⁵ - α⁴?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:49.560 --> 00:08:54.300
This negative sign means that it's not&nbsp;
allowed, even though we could simplify&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:54.300 --> 00:09:01.470
this to α⁴ + α⁵. If we did that, then it would be&nbsp;
a positive polynomial, but right now, it's not.

00:09:01.470 --> 00:09:08.490
So we're being very fussy, we're being&nbsp;
very clear. We're only allowing objects&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:08.490 --> 00:09:13.320
that fulfill the specifications of&nbsp;
the definition. This is a very good&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:13.320 --> 00:09:17.040
attitude to have when you're laying&nbsp;
the foundations for mathematics.

00:09:17.040 --> 00:09:25.290
Next time we're going to talk about factoring&nbsp;
positive polynomials or positive poly numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:25.290 --> 00:09:30.720
I hope you'll join me for that. I'm&nbsp;
Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

00:09:30.720 --> 00:09:30.750
[Music]

